193 Section 3. Sections 37-1-81.1, 37-1-81.2, and 37-1-81.3
194 are added to the Code of Alabama 1975 to read as follows:
195 §37-1-81.1
196 (a) The retail base rates established and in place on
Page 7

(a) The retail base rates established and in place on
HB475 Enrolled
197 October 1, 2026 for each utility that is regulated by the
198 commission and that provides retail electric service may not
199 be increased before January 1, 2029.
200 (b) On and after January 1, 2029, a utility that
201 provides retail electric service may not factor the following
202 costs into the calculation or determination of a new rate or
203 service regulation or a change to an existing rate or service
204 regulation charged to customers of the utility:
205 (1) Costs incurred due to the utility providing funding
206 or grants that impact rates to other persons or organizations.
207 (2) Costs incurred due to the hiring of persons for the
208 purpose of lobbying the Legislature or any other political
209 office or subdivision of the state.
210 (3) Costs incurred due to advertisement of the utility
211 other than public safety advertising approved by the
212 commission.
213 (c)(1) When an electric utility files a new schedule to
214 put in operation a new rate or service regulation or to change
215 an existing rate or service regulation, the utility shall
216 affirm that the utility has not included the prohibited costs
217 under subsection (b) in the calculation or determination of
218 the rate or service regulation.
219 (2) If the electric utility fails to make the
220 affirmation, the rate or service regulation shall be void.
221 (d) If the commission discovers that a utility has
222 included the prohibited cost under subsection (b) in the
223 calculation or determination of rates or service regulations,
224 the commission shall investigate the determination pursuant to
Page 8

the commission shall investigate the determination pursuant to
HB475 Enrolled
225 Section 37-1-83 and other powers of investigation granted to
226 the commission pursuant to this division.
227 §37-1-81.2
228 The commissioners and staff of the commission shall
229 convene at least one public meeting per calendar year with
230 utility representatives to provide information to the public
231 on cost trends, reliability, resilience, general
232 infrastructure investment plans, economic development impacts,
233 security of the power grid, national trends in energy
234 production, and other regulatory issues the Secretary of
235 Energy deems relevant. The public meetings shall be conducted
236 in a manner that gives residents the opportunity to
237 participate, addresses concerns voiced by the public, and
238 provides a review of key issues that the secretary believes
239 will be helpful to the public in understanding issues that
240 impact services under its jurisdiction.
241 §37-1-81.3
242 (a) After the mandated prohibition on increasing retail
243 base rates that runs until January 1, 2029, as provided in
244 Section 37-1-81.1, a formal hearing to examine specific issues
245 relative to the rate making process and to provide greater
246 transparency and direction to the establishment of base retail
247 rates, with testimony provided under oath, shall be triggered
248 upon the occurrence of:
249 (1) An affirmative vote of at least five commissioners
250 designating the issues to be examined and the timing and scope
251 of the formal hearing; or
252 (2) The direction of the Secretary of Energy specifying
Page 9

(2) The direction of the Secretary of Energy specifying
HB475 Enrolled
253 the issues to be examined and the timing and scope of the
254 formal hearing.
255 (b) In determining whether to conduct a formal hearing,
256 the secretary and the commissioners shall consider all
257 relevant factors, including:
258 (1) The base retail rate customers pay relative to the
259 national average;
260 (2) The base retail rate customers pay relative to the
261 regional average;
262 (3) Customer satisfaction reports;
263 (4) Reliability of the power grid;
264 (5) Operational efficiency of generating facilities;
265 (6) Capacity to accommodate economic development
266 priorities; and
267 (7) The relevant utility's credit rating and ability to
268 raise necessary capital.
269 (c) The secretary and commissioners, when implementing
270 the provisions of this section, shall have the power to
271 administer oaths under penalty of perjury and issue subpoenas
272 pursuant to Section 37-1-63.
